.TH ASK 1 "" "ask" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
ask \- themed terminal dialogs for scripts (confirm/line/text/choose/form)
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBask\fR \fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR ...] [\fIFLAGS\fR ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
ask exposes ai\-playbook's themed dialog widgets as a standalone tool for
shell scripts. Its contract is pure I/O: the submitted value (if any) goes
to stdout and nothing else, diagnostics go to stderr, and the exit code
reports the outcome — see EXIT CODES below.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS "ask confirm"
.PP
\fBask confirm "Prompt" [flags]\fR
.PP
yes/no dialog; the exit code is the answer (0 yes, 1 no, 130 cancel)
.TP
\fB\-\-danger\fR
danger variant (forces default=negative)
.TP
\fB\-\-warning\fR
warning variant
.TP
\fB\-\-affirmative\fR \fI<label>\fR
affirmative button label (default Yes)
.TP
\fB\-\-negative\fR \fI<label>\fR
negative button label (default No)
.TP
\fB\-\-default\fR \fIaffirmative|negative\fR
default focus (default affirmative)
.TP
\fB\-\-print\fR
also print yes/no to stdout
.SS "ask line"
.PP
\fBask line "Prompt" [flags]\fR
.PP
one\-line input; the submitted value is printed to stdout
.TP
\fB\-\-value\fR \fI<v>\fR
initial value
.TP
\fB\-\-placeholder\fR \fI<p>\fR
placeholder text
.TP
\fB\-\-icon\fR \fI<glyph>\fR
prompt\-column glyph override
.SS "ask text"
.PP
\fBask text "Prompt" [flags]\fR
.PP
multi\-line editor; the submitted value is printed to stdout
.TP
\fB\-\-value\fR \fI<v>\fR
initial value
.TP
\fB\-\-height\fR \fI<rows>\fR
editor viewport rows (default 10)
.TP
\fB\-\-icon\fR \fI<glyph>\fR
prompt\-column glyph override
.SS "ask choose"
.PP
\fBask choose "Prompt" <item>... [flags]\fR
.PP
select from items; selection printed to stdout (\-\-multi one per line)
.TP
\fB\-\-multi\fR
allow multiple selections (one per line)
.TP
\fB\-\-other\fR \fI<label>\fR
enable a free\-text entry row
.SS "ask form"
.PP
\fBask form [flags]\fR
.PP
multi\-field form from a JSON spec; key=value lines (or \-\-json)
.TP
\fB\-\-spec\fR \fI<file>\fR
JSON spec file; omit to read stdin
.TP
\fB\-\-json\fR
emit one JSON object instead of key=value lines
.SH "FLAGS (every subcommand)"
.PP
Every subcommand additionally accepts:
.TP
\fB\-\-title\fR \fI<t>\fR
modal title
.TP
\fB\-\-width\fR \fI<cols>\fR
pane width for measurement/sizing
.TP
\fB\-\-padding\fR \fI<rows>\fR
frame vertical padding rows
.TP
\fB\-\-inset\fR \fI<rows>\fR
frame inter\-section blank rows
.TP
\fB\-\-measure\fR
print the rendered height and exit (no TUI)
.SH THEMING
.PP
Every \-\-theme\-* flag has an ASK_<FLAG> environment fallback, so a script can
export the palette once instead of passing it on every invocation.
.PP
Precedence: flag > ASK_<FLAG> environment variable > built\-in default.
.PP
A SET\-but\-empty ASK_<FLAG> variable deliberately overrides the default with
the empty string: presence wins, not non\-emptiness. Exporting
\&'ASK_THEME_ACCENT=""' intentionally blanks that color; leaving the variable
unset (not exported at all) keeps the built\-in default.
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-accent\fR \fI<hex>\fR
title accent color (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_ACCENT)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-border\fR \fI<hex>\fR
default border/focus color (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_BORDER)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-danger\fR \fI<hex>\fR
danger variant color (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_DANGER)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-warning\fR \fI<hex>\fR
warning variant color (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_WARNING)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-base\fR \fI<hex>\fR
dark fg for warning focused button (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_BASE)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-text\fR \fI<hex>\fR
body text color (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_TEXT)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-muted\fR \fI<hex>\fR
hint words / comment color (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_MUTED)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-rule\fR \fI<hex>\fR
title rule / scroll track color (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_RULE)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-key\fR \fI<hex>\fR
hint key\-binding color (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_KEY)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-field\-border\fR \fI<hex>\fR
inner input box border (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_FIELD_BORDER)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-button\-bg\fR \fI<hex>\fR
unselected button bg (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_BUTTON_BG)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-button\-fg\fR \fI<hex>\fR
unselected button fg (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_BUTTON_FG)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-button\-sel\-bg\fR \fI<hex>\fR
selected button bg (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_BUTTON_SEL_BG)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-button\-sel\-fg\fR \fI<hex>\fR
selected button fg (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_BUTTON_SEL_FG)
.TP
\fB\-\-theme\-scroll\-thumb\fR \fI<hex>\fR
scroll thumb color (hex) (environment fallback: ASK_THEME_SCROLL_THUMB)
.SH "FLAG PARSING"
.PP
Flags may appear before OR after a subcommand's positional argument(s) —
e.g. both 'ask confirm \-\-danger "Delete?"' and 'ask confirm "Delete?"
\-\-danger' are equivalent.
.PP
A bare '\-\-' terminates flag parsing: everything after the FIRST '\-\-' is
taken verbatim as positional arguments and never re\-parsed as a flag.
.PP
A flag that needs a value which itself starts with '\-' (or is exactly
\&'\-\-') MUST use the '\-\-flag=value' form, e.g. '\-\-negative=\-\-weird'. The
space form ('\-\-flag \-value') does NOT work — the dashed word is parsed as
its own flag (or positional) and the command errors loudly.
.SH "EXIT CODES"
.TP
\fB0\fR
Submit / affirmative answer.
.TP
\fB1\fR
confirm's negative answer, OR any other non\-usage runtime widget failure —
the two are indistinguishable by exit code alone (a runtime failure reuses
exit 1 rather than inventing a new code). This is the safe
direction for shell idioms like 'if ask confirm "..."; then': both a
genuine "No" and an unexpected failure take the same false branch. A
script that must tell them apart should check stderr.
.TP
\fB130\fR
Cancelled (Esc / Ctrl\-C).
.TP
\fB2\fR
Usage error (unknown subcommand/flag, malformed \-\-spec/stdin JSON form
spec), or no controlling terminal is reachable.
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
ask confirm "Delete the branch?" \-\-danger
.fi
.PP
.nf
name=$(ask line "Your name" \-\-value "$USER")
.fi
.PP
.nf
notes=$(ask text "Release notes")
.fi
.PP
.nf
env=$(ask choose "Target environment" staging production)
.fi
.PP
.nf
ask form \-\-spec ./fields.json \-\-json
.fi
.SH "SEE ALSO"
\fBai\-playbook\fR(1)
